Farmer Mac is looking for a Data Scientist with experience in data mining, analytics, statistical programming, quantitative modeling, algorithm building, and model implementation to fill a dynamic role in the Research department. The daily function of the Data Scientist is to translate raw, unstructured industry and internal portfolio data into meaningful insights and predictions that support business decisions to fuel growth and mission fulfillment.
Position Summary

This role will develop data models, algorithms, predictive analytics, reports, business intelligence objects, and visualizations to support business initiatives; provide routine maintenance and lifecycle management on existing models and BI objects; develop new tools to improve predictive analytics for across business lines; work with the IT and Operations teams to improve the accuracy and flow of company data; and thoroughly validate model and process changes. The Data Scientist will contribute to and maintain critical business models with exposure to an array of company departments, thus the position will have a high degree of visibility and responsibility.

Suitable candidates must be detail oriented and able to balance competing priorities with deadlines. Equally important is the ability to work with minimal supervision while bringing innovative ideas to improve the operations of the company. The ideal candidate believes in constant improvement and often seeks new skills and techniques to improve on her or his capabilities.

With Whom You Will Work

The position will report to the Chief Economist and Head of Strategy, Research, and Analytics and interface with many departments, providing a research and problem-solving function focused on improving processes and business opportunities. The Data Scientist will work closely with the Data, Business Development, Risk, FP&A, and IT departments to create and produce content in conjunction with business line needs. This role is moderately visible to senior management, and the departmental work products are often presented in company committee meetings as well as to the board of directors.

Where and When You Will Work


Work is to be conducted at Farmer Mac’s headquarters at 1999 K Street NW, Washington, DC. Business hours are Monday through Friday 8:30 am to 5:30 pm Eastern Time. Work outside of these times may be required for planned and unplanned activities for the purposes of completion of a time-sensitive project or attendance at off-site meetings or events.

Major Responsibilities
Develop, maintain, and validate analytical tools, models, and datasets used for monitoring and assessing market opportunities for Farmer Mac’s Agricultural Finance and Rural Infrastructure business lines (e.g., market activity cluster analysis, marketing spend effectiveness monitoring, interest rate market forecasting);
Maintain and enhance deployed quantitative and predictive models (e.g., credit-loss prediction models, binary prepayment models, etc.);
Develop custom data models and algorithms using a wide range of enterprise and industry data (e.g., lending workflow algorithms, geospatial regression analysis, customer and loan behavior anomaly detection, etc.);
Interpret data, analyze results using statistical techniques, and providing ongoing reporting;
Identify, analyze, and interpret trends or patterns in complex data sets; and
Participate in and help guide the enterprise data governance framework.

Desired Skills & Qualifications
Some working experience as a Data Scientist or Data Analyst;
Knowledge of or experience building data models, statistical modeling, data mining, and segmentation techniques;
Knowledge of and experience with reporting packages (PowerBI, Excel, Business Objects, SQL Reporting Studio, etc.), databases (Microsoft SQL, Oracle, etc), programming (SAS, R, Python, etc.);
Knowledge of a variety of machine learning techniques (clustering, decision tree learning, artificial neural networks, etc.) and their real-world advantages/drawbacks
Strong analytical skills, including the ability to collect, organize, evaluate, and disseminate significant amounts of information with attention to detail and accuracy;
High proficiency or expertise in primary MS Office applications (Excel, Word, PowerPoint, Access); and
Self-starter with good communication and critical thinking skills.
Education and Experience
2+ years of professional data analysis, research, and reporting experience, preferably with exposure to finance, mortgages, or fixed income analysis;
Bachelor’s degree in economics, mathematics, statistics, engineering, finance, computer science, or business;
Advanced degrees in data science, statistical modeling, or economics will be considered as work experience;
Knowledge of or experience with R, Python, and Microsoft PowerBI preferred.
